Project Python Foundations: FoodHub Data Analysis¶

Context¶

The number of restaurants in New York is increasing day by day. Lots of students and busy professionals rely on those restaurants due to their hectic lifestyles. Online food delivery service is a great option for them. It provides them with good food from their favorite restaurants. A food aggregator company FoodHub offers access to multiple restaurants through a single smartphone app.

The app allows the restaurants to receive a direct online order from a customer. The app assigns a delivery person from the company to pick up the order after it is confirmed by the restaurant. The delivery person then uses the map to reach the restaurant and waits for the food package. Once the food package is handed over to the delivery person, he/she confirms the pick-up in the app and travels to the customer's location to deliver the food. The delivery person confirms the drop-off in the app after delivering the food package to the customer. The customer can rate the order in the app. The food aggregator earns money by collecting a fixed margin of the delivery order from the restaurants.

Objective¶

The food aggregator company has stored the data of the different orders made by the registered customers in their online portal. They want to analyze the data to get a fair idea about the demand of different restaurants which will help them in enhancing their customer experience. Suppose you are hired as a Data Scientist in this company and the Data Science team has shared some of the key questions that need to be answered. Perform the data analysis to find answers to these questions that will help the company to improve the business.

Data Description¶

The data contains the different data related to a food order. The detailed data dictionary is given below.

Data Dictionary¶

  • order_id: Unique ID of the order
  • customer_id: ID of the customer who ordered the food
  • restaurant_name: Name of the restaurant
  • cuisine_type: Cuisine ordered by the customer
  • cost_of_the_order: Cost of the order
  • day_of_the_week: Indicates whether the order is placed on a weekday or weekend (The weekday is from Monday to Friday and the weekend is Saturday and Sunday)
  • rating: Rating given by the customer out of 5
  • food_preparation_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the restaurant to prepare the food. This is calculated by taking the difference between the timestamps of the restaurant's order confirmation and the delivery person's pick-up confirmation.
  • delivery_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the delivery person to deliver the food package. This is calculated by taking the difference between the timestamps of the delivery person's pick-up confirmation and drop-off information

# replacing values with nan
data['rating'] = data['rating'].replace(['Not given'],np.nan)

data['rating'] = data['rating'].astype(float)

Cuisine vs Cost of the order¶

In [45]:
#Boxplot of distribution of cost of the order by cuisine type, ordered by most popular cuisines
plt.figure(figsize = (10,5))
sns.boxplot(data=data,x='cuisine_type',y='cost_of_the_order', order=data.cuisine_type.value_counts().index)
plt.xticks(rotation=90)
plt.show()
  • There seems to be no obvious relationship between the popularity of the cuisine and the cost of the order, since some of the cheapest cuisines are Vietnamese, Korean, Mexican and Mediterranean but they are not the most popular.
  • The cuisines Mediterranean and Korean seem to have the most outliers in the data, with Mediterranean having the highest order cost.
  • French cuisine has the highest interquartile range but the first and third quartile are almost the same as the minimum and maximum cost of the order.
  • The top 4 cuisines American, Japanese, Italian and Chinese all seem to have their median price around 15 dollars and spread of the data around the same values.
  • The most expensive cuisine by median price is a close call between Thai and Spanish food. The least expensive cuisine by median price is also very close between Korean and Vietnamese.
  • The most popular cuisines tend to be neither the most expensive nor the

least expensive.

Day of the Week vs Delivery time¶

In [48]:
#Boxplot of distribution of delivery time by day of the week
plt.figure(figsize = (5,8))
sns.boxplot(data=data,x='day_of_the_week',y='delivery_time')
plt.show()
  • On weekdays the delivery time is much higher than that of weekends.
  • On weekends there tends to be a higher variance in delivery time but lower median delivery time.
  • 75% of the orders on weekdays are delivered within 31 minutes or less, but 75% of orders on the weekends are delivered within around 26 minutes or less.
  • This is probably indicative of the higher resources allocated to the weekends in order to cope with more demand and cover more delivery range, considering also that there were many more orders made on the weekend than the weekdays. This explains the likely higher variance and lower median delivery time.

Rating vs Delivery time¶

In [49]:
#Boxplot of distribution of delivery time by rating
#plt.figure(figsize = (5,10))
sns.pointplot(data=data,x='rating',y='delivery_time')
plt.show()
  • Orders with higher delivery time tend to have a rating of 3, while the lower delivery times have an average of 4.
  • There is no obvious relationship between the increase of delivery time and the rating.
  • High delivery times likely cause the customer to give the order a lower rating, but other factors may come into play when a customer gives a rating between 4 and 5 despite having low delivery times.
  • It is worthwhile noting that the difference in delivery times between these ratings is very little, all within the same minute or so, hence the data may not give us much insight between delivery time and rating. It may be safe to conclude that the relationship is negligible.

Correlation among variables¶

In [53]:
#Heatmap to show correlation between the three numerical variables: Cost of the order, food delivery time and food preparation time
col_list = ['cost_of_the_order', 'food_preparation_time', 'delivery_time']
sns.heatmap(data[col_list].corr(),annot=True,cmap='Spectral',vmin=-1,vmax=1)
plt.show()
  • The cost of the order and the food preparation time have a small positive correlation of 3.5%, which is very weak.
  • The cost of the order and delivery time have a negative correlation of 7.6%, which is also weak.
  • The delivery time and food preparation time has a very low negative correlation of 0.86%, which indicates that they hardly affect each other at all.
  • From this heatmap an correlation analysis, it is safe to conclude that none of the numerical variables in our dataset have a strong correlation with each other.

Question 13: The company wants to provide a promotional offer in the advertisement of the restaurants. The condition to get the offer is that the restaurants must have a rating count of more than 50 and the average rating should be greater than 4. Find the restaurants fulfilling the criteria to get the promotional offer. [3 marks]¶

In [54]:
#Restaurants with rating count more than 50
restaurants_rating_count_50 = data.groupby(['restaurant_name'])['rating'].count()
restaurants_rating_count_50 = restaurants_rating_count_50[restaurants_rating_count_50 > 50].reset_index()

#Restaurants with average rating greater than 4
restaurants_rating_4 = data.groupby(['restaurant_name'])['rating'].mean()
restaurants_rating_4 = restaurants_rating_4[restaurants_rating_4 > 4].reset_index()

qualifying_resturants = restaurants_rating_count_50.merge(restaurants_rating_4, left_on='restaurant_name', right_on='restaurant_name', how='inner')
qualifying_resturants
Out[54]:
restaurant_name rating_x rating_y
0 Blue Ribbon Fried Chicken 64 4.328125
1 Blue Ribbon Sushi 73 4.219178
2 Shake Shack 133 4.278195
3 The Meatball Shop 84 4.511905

Observations:¶

  • First using a groupby to get the restaurants with at least 50 ratings and then using groupby again to get restaurants with at least 4.0 average rating, and then doing an inner join on both lists gives us the list of restaurants that qualify for the promotion.
  • Hence the restaurants that fulfil the criteria for the promotion are Blue Ribbon Fried Chicken, Blue Ribbon Sushi, Shake Shack and The Meatball Shop.

Question 14: The company charges the restaurant 25% on the orders having cost greater than 20 dollars and 15% on the orders having cost greater than 5 dollars. Find the net revenue generated by the company across all orders. [3 marks]¶

In [56]:
# Calculate an extra column in the data frame to generate the extra revenue per order
data['cost_20'] = np.where(data['cost_of_the_order'] > 20, 0.25 * data['cost_of_the_order'], 0)
data['cost_5'] = np.where((data['cost_of_the_order'] > 5) & (data['cost_of_the_order'] <= 20), 0.15 * data['cost_of_the_order'], 0)
data['extra_revenue'] = data['cost_20'] + data['cost_5']
data.sample(5)

Conclusion and Recommendations¶

Question 17: What are your conclusions from the analysis? What recommendations would you like to share to help improve the business? (You can use cuisine type and feedback ratings to drive your business recommendations.) [6 marks]¶

Conclusions:¶

  • The most popular cuisines are American, Japanese and Italian.
  • In general there is an average to high satisfaction rate among customers
  • The variance of delivery time and food preparation time is not very high and does not have outliers, indicating that the orders are well managed overall.
  • There is no significant correlation between delivery time, food preparation time and cost of the order.
  • The most popular restaurants by number of orders are Shake Shack, The Meatball Shop, Blue Ribbon Sushi, Blue Ribbon Fried Chicken and RedFarm Broadway.
  • In terms of restaurants and their revenues, Kabi Ramen House has the highest average cost and Haandi has the lowest average cost per order while Shake Shack has made the most money while Haandi has made the least.
  • Majority of the orders are made during the weekends
  • The delivery time varies depending on the day of the week, higher on average during the weekdays when compared to the weekends.

Recommendations:¶

Based on the exploratory data anlysis, the business can find patterns in the customer behaviour and potentially act on the following recommendations

  • Incentivize more sales on the weekdays with lower cost and better delivery times
  • Promote the most popular restaurants using marketing campaigns, loyalty programs, discounts for regular customers.
  • Deducing what are the most popular restaurants and quickest total time for restaurants for both weekends and weekdays and suggest those to customers for higher ratings.
  • Incentivize users to rate the orders because of large missing data. The more data there is, the better the analysis we can do. Potentially adding a discount for every 10 reviews or something similar.
